message.content: For every positive natural number $x$, the absolute difference between the sum of the sequence $\left(\frac{\text{del}(n)}{n}\right)$ from $n = 0$ to $x - 1$ and the expression $\frac{2x}{3}$ is less than 1.

For every natural number $x$ greater than zero, the absolute difference between the sum of the sequence $\sum_{n \in \text{Finset.range}(x)} \frac{\text{del}(n)}{n}$ and $\frac{2x}{3}$ is less than 1.

The theorem states that for every natural number $x$ greater than zero, the absolute difference between the sum of $\frac{\text{del}(n)}{n}$ over all integers $n$ from $0$ to $x-1$ and $\frac{2x}{3}$ is less than $1$.
For any natural number $x$ greater than 0, the absolute difference between the sum $\sum_{n \in \text{Finset.range}(x)} \frac{\text{del}(n)}{n}$ and $\frac{2x}{3}$ is less than 1.
For any natural number $x$ greater than 0, the absolute difference between the sum $\sum_{n \in \{0, 1, \ldots, x-1\}} \frac{\text{del}(n)}{n}$ and $\frac{2x}{3}$ is less than 1.

For every natural number $x$, if $x$ is greater than 0, then the absolute value of the difference between the sum of \(\frac{\text{del}(n)}{n}\) over \(n\) in the range from 0 to \(x-1\) and \(\frac{2x}{3}\) is less than 1.

For every natural number $x$ such that $x > 0$, the absolute difference between the sum of the sequence $\sum_{n \in \text{Finset.range } x} \frac{\text{del}(n)}{n}$ and $\frac{2x}{3}$ is less than 1.
For any natural number $x$ greater than 0, the absolute value of the sum $\sum_{n \in \{0, 1, \ldots, x-1\}} \frac{\text{del}(n)}{n}$ minus $\frac{2x}{3}$ is less than 1.
For any positive natural number $x$, the absolute value of the sum of $\frac{\text{del}(n)}{n}$ over $n$ in the range from $0$ to $x-1$, minus $\frac{2x}{3}$, is less than $1$.
For every natural number $x$ greater than zero, the absolute difference between the sum of the series $\sum_{n \in \text{Finset.range}(x)} \frac{\text{del}(n)}{n}$ and $\frac{2x}{3}$ is less than 1.
